  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let your patient crash; give them their stress dose!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because patients with pituitary-adrenal suppression due to exogenous steroid use require stress-dose steroid replacement during surgery to prevent adrenal crisis. A regimen of 100 mg hydrocortisone IV every 6 hours is a standard initial approach for adequate perioperative coverage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic exogenous steroid use suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, rendering the body unable to produce sufficient cortisol in response to surgical stress. This can lead to an adrenal crisis, characterized by hypotension, hypoglycemia, and electrolyte disturbances. Administering 100 mg hydrocortisone IV q6h provides the necessary glucocorticoid coverage to support vital functions and maintain hemodynamic stability during the acute stress of surgery and immediate postoperative period, mimicking the body's natural stress response.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Halving the postoperative steroid dose every 12 hours is too rapid and significantly increases the risk of adrenal insufficiency or crisis. Tapering should be much slower, typically every 48 to 72 hours, to allow for gradual HPA axis recovery.\nOption C (Incorrect): There is no evidence to suggest that prophylactic treatment with a somatostatin analogue reduces the risk of postoperative pancreatitis in the context of steroid management. While pancreatitis is a known complication, somatostatin analogues are not indicated for its prevention here.\nOption D (Incorrect): The pituitary-adrenal axis can remain suppressed for a prolonged period, often 6 to 12 months, after cessation of exogenous steroids. Stopping replacement after only 3 months would likely lead to adrenal insufficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Aspect | Correct Management | Incorrect/Misconception |\n|---|---|---|\n| Initial Stress Dose | 100 mg Hydrocortisone IV q6h | Insufficient or delayed dosing |\n| Postoperative Tapering | Halve dose every 48-72 hours | Halving every 12 hours (too fast) |\n| HPA Axis Recovery | 6-12 months | Only 3 months (too short) |\n| Pancreatitis Prophylaxis | No specific drug (e.g., somatostatin) | Somatostatin analogue (no evidence) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stress-dose steroids prevent adrenal crisis; taper slowly, not quickly.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging is directly relevant to this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: \"Management of Glucocorticoid-Induced Adrenal Insufficiency\" (2016). It recommends stress-dose glucocorticoid replacement for patients with adrenal insufficiency undergoing surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | On the day of surgery he should receive 100 mg hydrocortisone IV q6h | ✅ Correct |\n| B | The postoperative steroid dose should be halved q 12 hours to reduce the ri | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Prophylactic treatment with a somatostatin analogue will reduce the risk of | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Exogenous steroid replacement can be stopped after 3 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The postoperative course of management for a patient with pituitary adrenal suppression from exogeno** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385388882-1 copy.pdf**\n",
